<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">40854076</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>02</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>02</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2769-707X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>45</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of the American Nutrition Association</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Am Nutr Assoc</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Diet-Controlled Whey Protein Supplementation: Mitigating Serum Creatine Kinase Levels After Continuous Resistance Exercise.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>158</StartPage><EndPage>164</EndPage><MedlinePgn>158-164</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/27697061.2025.2548514</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">As awareness of the health benefits of resistance exercise grows, an increasing number of people are participating, but eccentric movements in such exercises can cause muscle damage. This study aimed to investigate the effects of whey protein supplementation on resistance exercise-induced serum creatine kinase (CK) increase.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Cross-sectional study with repeated measures intervention lasting 1&#x2009;week.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Thirty-six men were randomly assigned to a protein supplement group (PSG) or a placebo group (CON). Participants consumed three packed meals with protein supplement or placebo daily. Resistance exercise (60% 1-RM intensity) occurred for 60&#x2009;min over 6 consecutive days. Blood was collected at baseline, within 1-h post-exercise for 6&#x2009;days, and 24&#x2009;h after the final session.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">There was a significant group-by-time interaction (<i>p</i>&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.049). In PSG, there were no significant changes in serum CK levels at any consecutive time points. However, a significant increase in serum CK levels was observed exclusively in CON from 0 to 24&#x2009;h after exercise (from 551.4&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;323.4 to 1244.8&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;1203.6, <i>p</i>&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.036), and also from 24 to 48&#x2009;h after exercise (from 1244.8&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;1203.6 to 7480.2&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;9173.0, <i>p</i>&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.044). Additionally, a significant decrease was noted only in CON from 96 to 120&#x2009;h after exercise (from 12696.3&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;10438.4 to 9957.8&#x2009;&#xb1;&#x2009;9176.6, <i>p</i>&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.023). Serum CK levels on the last day were lower in PSG than in CON (<i>p</i>&#x2009;=&#x2009;0.023).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">In conclusion, whey protein supplementation may have a positive effect in mitigating the serum CK increase induced by six consecutive days of resistance exercise.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kim</LastName><ForeName>Chae-Been</ForeName><Initials>CB</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-8811-929X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Sport Science, Pusan National University, Busan, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ahn</LastName><ForeName>Dohyun</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0008-0986-3036</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Sport Science, Pusan National University, Busan, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kim</LastName><ForeName>Ji-Been</ForeName><Initials>JB</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1059-731X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Health Wellness, Yuhan University, Gyeonggi-do, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Park</LastName><ForeName>Hyoung-Su</ForeName><Initials>HS</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-7205-1366</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>R&amp;D Group, Maeil Health Nutrition Co., Ltd, Pyeongtaek, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kim</LastName><ForeName>Hye-Jin</ForeName><Initials>HJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-5931-1258</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>R&amp;D Group, Maeil Health Nutrition Co., Ltd, Pyeongtaek, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Park</LastName><ForeName>Jung-Jun</ForeName><Initials>JJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-2518-7225</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Sport Science, Pusan National University, Busan, Republic of Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>25</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>J Am Nutr Assoc</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>9918300687506676</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>2769-7061</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>0</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D000067816">Whey Proteins</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>EC 2.7.3.2</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D003402">Creatine Kinase</NameOfSubstance></Chemical></ChemicalList><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D006801" MajorTopicYN="N">Humans</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorNam